</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I attended the Chicago Fan Faire this weekend, and there were several good sessions. I&#8217;ll try to summarize what I recall. 
<br />

<br />
Peridots. The devs acknowledged that this is an unfair cash burden on clerics, and will reexamine it. At the same time, they said that cash sinks are badly needed, and if anyone has ideas of a cash sink that would be popular (ie, people would voluntarily spend the plat) to please send them to Dev Corner. 
<br />

<br />
Duck on horses. Sitting med whilst on a horse was an unintended benefit, inability to duck out is an unintended negative. They said horses were intended to be a cash sink that provided run speed and the ability to say &#8216;look! I have a horse!&#8217; and nothing more, and thus consider the two unintended effects to be linked. If they remove one, they&#8217;ll remove the other, and they figure most people would prefer that both be left. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Clerical boredom. When I brought up that healing needs are finite, and clerics need something else to do, the reaction was: yaulp/melee/summoned hammer, mok, pet hammer, pacify. When I pointed out that my clerics are only 51 and 52, thus having none of the above but pacify, and had been bored since 40, they wrote down that clerics between 40 and 54 need love. /shrug Hard to predict on that one, but they did note it so perhaps something will be done so that rising clerics don&#8217;t give up before they ever get to 55. 
<br />

<br />
The ability to get mana in the high end is already way too easy. They will not be increasing the flowing thought cap (or the attack modifier cap? Something like that), nor will they give wizards an improved harvest, etc. It wasn&#8217;t open to debate. 
<br />

<br />
Feign dead is unpopular, so not a chance in hell for beastlords to get it or for necros to get a bestow feign &#8211; both requesters were laughed out of the room. 
<br />

<br />
Complete Heal is a broken spell, especially being level 39. They hate it. They are desperately working at implementing new lines of heals in the hopes of mitigating (or perhaps replacing entirely?) complete heal. My impression was that the goal was to actually remove complete heal entirely, but I&#8217;m not sure that&#8217;s even doable (can they remove spells from spell books? They never have), and they didn&#8217;t actually say that&#8230;&#8230; But the druid who asked for their &#8216;complete heal&#8217; to have it&#8217;s cast time reduced was told NO quite emphatically. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
LdoN 
<br />
They are very excited about the potential all the new systems gives them. They are quite likely to add new themes/adventure types etc, either as part of ldon or in other areas, current or future. (They shared no info about the next expansion other then that there is one). All the devs there seemed to be raiders, but they have considerably more information about their player base then they used to (and I think they were surprised by what they found out). They noted that LoY and LdoN were aimed at the middle base more then the high end simply because that turned out to be the majority of their players. However, the LDoN raids ARE aimed entirely at the high end folk, especially Time, (as was the final zone in LoY) because they are the ones eating through content fastest. They indicated the next expansion should keep those folk happy. 
<br />

<br />
There are 3 types of raids, each balanced for 36 people with a given level of gear: HARD is Time geared balanced; Normal is actually two different levels: VT gear balanced on the low end, and an inbetween (Elemental I think, not sure). Each raid giver gives only one of those 3 levels, so next patch they&#8217;ll make it a bit clearer &#8211; if it says hard it means Time, if it says normal you get to figure out which of the two apply. 
<br />

<br />
The systems are complicated, but they feel that the in-game information isn&#8217;t doing a satisfactory job of conveying what&#8217;s going on, so look for a long Dev Corner post, as well as some tweaking of what&#8217;s said. 
<br />

<br />
Confirmed that once you &#8216;open&#8217; a theme, you can spend points from other themes, it doesn&#8217;t keep track of the source. Confirmed that they are adjusting upwards the number of points for &#8216;hard&#8217; adventures. They are also working on the traps, which are not working as intended. They have reams of data, much more so then for any prior expansion. Each night they get a report showing themes and adventure types taken, succeeded, failed etc by level. Also, coin gained and exp earned as well as AP earned. Some driven person earned 1500 AP in a single day. The high exp was planned. The plat at 65 is higher then desired, expect it to be tweaked downwards. They also will be tweaking things to make adventure themes and types equally desireable, as planned. 
<br />

<br />
The 30 second delay between requests is &#8216;how it works&#8217; &#8211; basically, they spawn the instance when you request an adventure (to make sure you actually get one) and the delay is for cleaning it up if you decline. Since the 30 minutes &#8216;extra&#8217; time is being used with enthusiasm, they are going to find a way to provide a timer, but not right away. The &#8216;too dangerous&#8217; message is a bug &#8211; it was intended for glitches where the instance hasn&#8217;t fully spawned yet, so you just need to wait a minute. What&#8217;s happening is the instance is getting the message when the instance just never started at all. Message fixed on test, they also think they have fixed whatever causes the instance to never start in the first place. 
<br />

<br />
Drop rates for collection: the &#8216;seed&#8217; is 1.5x, where x is the number of items requested. Should you ever completely clear an adventure and not get the right number, /bug it. It has been reported elsewhere that the drops are also on the trap/follower mobs, which I would suggest /bugging too, I don&#8217;t think that&#8217;s intended (since they don&#8217;t count for slaughters). 
<br />

<br />
They completely rewrote /bug and /feedback for the LdoN beta, and swear that they now work very well, and would everyone please use them. In particular, use /bug in the zone/adventure the error occurs so more data is collected. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Melee balance is in progress. Taunt is broken. Knights and Warriors are out of synch. Casters are not going to get any tweaks until melees have been fixed. That was all they would say. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
